00:40:23.906 --> 00:40:25.796 A:middle
So there's some things you can

00:40:25.796 --> 00:40:26.956 A:middle
do for the voluntary case as

00:40:26.956 --> 00:40:27.196 A:middle
well.

00:40:27.286 --> 00:40:28.516 A:middle
So when a user has actually

00:40:28.516 --> 00:40:29.896 A:middle
voluntarily elected to

00:40:29.896 --> 00:40:31.076 A:middle
unsubscribe from your app, you

00:40:31.076 --> 00:40:32.306 A:middle
can use this information to help

00:40:32.306 --> 00:40:32.976 A:middle
you here as well.

00:40:33.736 --> 00:40:34.916 A:middle
There's that expiration intent

00:40:34.916 --> 00:40:35.956 A:middle
field that we're including now

00:40:36.006 --> 00:40:37.406 A:middle
and you can use this as a way to

00:40:37.406 --> 00:40:38.436 A:middle
offer messaging to those

00:40:38.436 --> 00:40:39.346 A:middle
particular users.

00:40:40.096 --> 00:40:41.166 A:middle
So let's say that a user

00:40:41.166 --> 00:40:41.586 A:middle
canceled.

00:40:42.376 --> 00:40:43.996 A:middle
You can maybe think well, let's

00:40:43.996 --> 00:40:45.256 A:middle
apply some kind of win back.

00:40:46.206 --> 00:40:47.366 A:middle
Maybe you rolled out a price

00:40:47.366 --> 00:40:49.246 A:middle
increase and the user expired

00:40:49.246 --> 00:40:50.566 A:middle
because they didn't consent to

00:40:50.566 --> 00:40:50.636 A:middle
it.

00:40:50.636 --> 00:40:52.206 A:middle
Well now you can offer maybe an

00:40:52.206 --> 00:40:53.306 A:middle
attractive downgrade option

00:40:53.306 --> 00:40:54.506 A:middle
because you know that it was

00:40:54.506 --> 00:40:55.266 A:middle
really about the price

00:40:55.266 --> 00:40:56.586 A:middle
difference that caused the user

00:40:56.586 --> 00:40:57.386 A:middle
to unsubscribe.

00:40:57.386 --> 00:40:58.786 A:middle
So you can see how you can use

00:40:58.996 --> 00:40:59.676 A:middle
just in these couple of

00:40:59.676 --> 00:41:00.976 A:middle
examples, these fields to now,

00:41:01.386 --> 00:41:02.306 A:middle
you know, make key business

00:41:02.306 --> 00:41:03.536 A:middle
decisions and how you interact

00:41:03.536 --> 00:41:04.686 A:middle
with your users and save

00:41:04.926 --> 00:41:05.636 A:middle
subscription churn.

00:41:07.596 --> 00:41:08.786 A:middle
These new fields are arriving

00:41:08.786 --> 00:41:10.046 A:middle
later this year along with the

00:41:10.046 --> 00:41:12.046 A:middle
server notifications and we

00:41:12.046 --> 00:41:13.176 A:middle
think this is going to give a

00:41:13.176 --> 00:41:14.556 A:middle
much better experience for all

00:41:14.556 --> 00:41:16.016 A:middle
users for your subscriptions and

00:41:16.016 --> 00:41:17.076 A:middle
for you developing it as well.

00:41:18.516 --> 00:41:24.546 A:middle
[ Clapping ]

00:41:25.046 --> 00:41:27.626 A:middle
They fit in this diagram as

00:41:27.626 --> 00:41:28.576 A:middle
another set of tools that you

00:41:28.576 --> 00:41:29.576 A:middle
can use for server side

00:41:29.576 --> 00:41:30.536 A:middle
subscription management

00:41:30.536 --> 00:41:31.716 A:middle
alongside the status polling

00:41:31.716 --> 00:41:32.446 A:middle
that we talked about.

00:41:32.446 --> 00:41:33.826 A:middle
But of course, you still need to

00:41:33.826 --> 00:41:35.616 A:middle
be relying on this flow of

00:41:35.616 --> 00:41:36.446 A:middle
updating and finishing

00:41:36.446 --> 00:41:38.276 A:middle
transactions on a user's device.

00:41:39.206 --> 00:41:40.546 A:middle
So while we're talking about

00:41:40.546 --> 00:41:41.476 A:middle
subscriptions, I just want to

00:41:41.476 --> 00:41:43.486 A:middle
touch on free trials for a

00:41:44.416 --> 00:41:44.646 A:middle
moment.

00:41:44.756 --> 00:41:45.936 A:middle
Free trial is when a user can

00:41:46.156 --> 00:41:47.366 A:middle
begin a subscription without

00:41:47.366 --> 00:41:48.746 A:middle
actually paying for anything.

00:41:49.176 --> 00:41:50.626 A:middle
And they are not billed until

00:41:50.626 --> 00:41:51.616 A:middle
the free trial period is

00:41:51.616 --> 00:41:52.106 A:middle
actually over.

00:41:53.566 --> 00:41:55.996 A:middle
So previously, we had this

00:41:56.476 --> 00:41:57.666 A:middle
pretty convoluted looking table

00:41:57.666 --> 00:41:59.136 A:middle
and you'd have an associated

00:41:59.136 --> 00:42:00.726 A:middle
free trial duration for a

00:42:00.726 --> 00:42:01.546 A:middle
subscription length.

00:42:01.876 --> 00:42:03.376 A:middle
And you had to choose which

00:42:03.376 --> 00:42:04.836 A:middle
trials you could offer based on

00:42:04.836 --> 00:42:05.716 A:middle
the subscription length that you

00:42:05.716 --> 00:42:06.536 A:middle
were offering users.

00:42:06.536 --> 00:42:07.416 A:middle
Now we made some changes

00:42:07.416 --> 00:42:08.956 A:middle
recently to make this much

00:42:08.956 --> 00:42:09.256 A:middle
simpler.

00:42:09.256 --> 00:42:10.606 A:middle
So you can now have any

00:42:10.606 --> 00:42:11.856 A:middle
subscription length available

00:42:11.856 --> 00:42:13.256 A:middle
for any free trial duration.

00:42:13.256 --> 00:42:14.596 A:middle
So we think is a much better

00:42:14.596 --> 00:42:16.206 A:middle
improvement and this includes

00:42:16.546 --> 00:42:18.106 A:middle
two new free trial durations as

00:42:18.106 --> 00:42:19.126 A:middle
well, which is the three-day

00:42:19.126 --> 00:42:20.576 A:middle
trial and the two-week trial.

00:42:20.576 --> 00:42:21.766 A:middle
These are two new trial

00:42:21.766 --> 00:42:22.766 A:middle
durations that you can offer to

00:42:22.766 --> 00:42:23.376 A:middle
your users.

00:42:23.926 --> 00:42:26.456 A:middle
So that's a bit about

00:42:26.456 --> 00:42:27.806 A:middle
maintaining subscription state

00:42:27.806 --> 00:42:28.996 A:middle
and talking about managing auto

00:42:28.996 --> 00:42:29.986 A:middle
renewable subscriptions in the

00:42:29.986 --> 00:42:30.236 A:middle
server.

00:42:30.236 --> 00:42:32.176 A:middle
I'd like to touch now on

00:42:32.266 --> 00:42:33.596 A:middle
developing in the sandbox

00:42:33.596 --> 00:42:34.116 A:middle
environment.

00:42:34.226 --> 00:42:35.076 A:middle
So how you can use these

00:42:35.076 --> 00:42:36.286 A:middle
technologies while you're

00:42:36.286 --> 00:42:36.746 A:middle
developing.

00:42:37.406 --> 00:42:38.796 A:middle
So what is the sandbox?

00:42:39.606 --> 00:42:40.556 A:middle
Well it's not to be confused

00:42:40.556 --> 00:42:41.726 A:middle
with the sandbox on your

00:42:41.726 --> 00:42:43.166 A:middle
application, on a user's device

00:42:43.206 --> 00:42:44.146 A:middle
that guards access to

00:42:44.146 --> 00:42:45.226 A:middle
application resources.

00:42:45.496 --> 00:42:47.736 A:middle
This particular sandbox is the

00:42:47.736 --> 00:42:48.806 A:middle
test environment that we offer

00:42:48.806 --> 00:42:50.176 A:middle
for you to test out in-app

00:42:50.176 --> 00:42:50.746 A:middle
purchases in.

00:42:51.406 --> 00:42:53.026 A:middle
And we select it based on the

00:42:53.026 --> 00:42:54.126 A:middle
certificate that's actually used

00:42:54.126 --> 00:42:55.216 A:middle
to sign your application.

00:42:55.726 --> 00:42:56.946 A:middle
It's how StoreKit knows whether

00:42:56.946 --> 00:42:58.236 A:middle
to be in a sandbox mode or not.

00:42:58.646 --> 00:43:00.446 A:middle
So if you build and run your app

00:43:00.446 --> 00:43:01.006 A:middle
from Xcode [phonetic].

00:43:01.006 --> 00:43:02.236 A:middle
It's signed using your developer

00:43:02.236 --> 00:43:03.656 A:middle
certificate and StoreKit knows

00:43:03.656 --> 00:43:04.846 A:middle
that it needs to be talking to

00:43:04.846 --> 00:43:05.916 A:middle
the sandbox environment.

00:43:06.016 --> 00:43:07.926 A:middle
Of course, if you distribute it

00:43:07.926 --> 00:43:09.776 A:middle
using the App Store, well

00:43:09.926 --> 00:43:10.896 A:middle
StoreKit knows that it needs to

00:43:10.896 --> 00:43:11.696 A:middle
talk to the production

00:43:11.696 --> 00:43:12.476 A:middle
environment based on the

00:43:12.476 --> 00:43:14.116 A:middle
certificate used to sign your

00:43:14.116 --> 00:43:14.306 A:middle
app.

00:43:15.546 --> 00:43:16.506 A:middle
And how do you know when you're

00:43:16.506 --> 00:43:18.026 A:middle
actually working with app which

00:43:18.076 --> 00:43:19.616 A:middle
environment you're in?

00:43:20.566 --> 00:43:21.426 A:middle
When you make your in-app

00:43:21.426 --> 00:43:22.276 A:middle
purchase inside your

00:43:22.276 --> 00:43:23.996 A:middle
application, you get this

00:43:23.996 --> 00:43:24.996 A:middle
payment sheet that we saw in

00:43:24.996 --> 00:43:25.756 A:middle
this morning's session.

00:43:26.666 --> 00:43:28.096 A:middle
And we have this indication here

00:43:28.096 --> 00:43:29.156 A:middle
that you're in sandbox mode.

00:43:29.156 --> 00:43:30.146 A:middle
So this is going to inform you

00:43:30.146 --> 00:43:31.336 A:middle
that the payment that's about to

00:43:31.336 --> 00:43:33.216 A:middle
take place is actually a sandbox

00:43:33.216 --> 00:43:34.676 A:middle
payment and no real money is

00:43:34.676 --> 00:43:35.936 A:middle
going to be changing hands.

00:43:36.506 --> 00:43:39.386 A:middle
So the key differences between

00:43:39.386 --> 00:43:40.446 A:middle
the sandbox and the production

00:43:40.446 --> 00:43:41.256 A:middle
environment, well the biggest

00:43:41.256 --> 00:43:42.006 A:middle
one, of course, is that there's

00:43:42.006 --> 00:43:43.556 A:middle
no real money being changed

00:43:43.556 --> 00:43:43.966 A:middle
hands here.

00:43:43.966 --> 00:43:45.376 A:middle
There's no actual charge

00:43:45.376 --> 00:43:45.726 A:middle
happening.

00:43:45.726 --> 00:43:46.866 A:middle
So you don't need to be charging

00:43:46.866 --> 00:43:48.036 A:middle
your personal card 10-cent

00:43:48.036 --> 00:43:49.476 A:middle
transactions all the time.

00:43:49.826 --> 00:43:51.266 A:middle
There's a different endpoint as

00:43:51.266 --> 00:43:51.886 A:middle
well when it comes to

00:43:51.886 --> 00:43:53.346 A:middle
server-to-server validation.

00:43:53.716 --> 00:43:54.946 A:middle
We provide a different url for

00:43:54.946 --> 00:43:56.266 A:middle
that verify receipt endpoint.

00:43:56.986 --> 00:43:58.346 A:middle
And you can also request expired

00:43:58.346 --> 00:43:59.896 A:middle
and revoked certificates in the

00:43:59.896 --> 00:44:01.036 A:middle
sandbox environment to be able

00:44:01.036 --> 00:44:01.776 A:middle
to handle them a little

00:44:01.776 --> 00:44:02.156 A:middle
differently.

00:44:03.376 --> 00:44:04.746 A:middle
The other thing that is

00:44:04.746 --> 00:44:06.336 A:middle
different is a time contraction

00:44:06.516 --> 00:44:07.146 A:middle
for auto renewable

00:44:07.146 --> 00:44:07.836 A:middle
subscriptions.

00:44:08.296 --> 00:44:09.276 A:middle
So instead of having to wait a

00:44:09.276 --> 00:44:10.726 A:middle
full year for a subscription to

00:44:10.726 --> 00:44:11.776 A:middle
renew to be able to test out

00:44:11.776 --> 00:44:13.096 A:middle
that scenario, we can track

00:44:13.146 --> 00:44:13.996 A:middle
these time intervals.

00:44:14.426 --> 00:44:15.856 A:middle
So the rule of thumb is that one

00:44:15.856 --> 00:44:17.056 A:middle
hour of time in the sandbox

00:44:17.056 --> 00:44:19.026 A:middle
world equals one year of time in

00:44:19.026 --> 00:44:19.606 A:middle
the real world.

00:44:19.606 --> 00:44:21.716 A:middle
And this is how those relate for

00:44:21.716 --> 00:44:22.466 A:middle
the various different

00:44:22.466 --> 00:44:23.576 A:middle
subscription durations.

00:44:24.096 --> 00:44:26.296 A:middle
The other thing that we do when

00:44:26.296 --> 00:44:27.406 A:middle
you're operating in a sandbox

00:44:27.406 --> 00:44:28.506 A:middle
environment is that if you are

00:44:28.506 --> 00:44:30.046 A:middle
subscribed to an auto renewable

00:44:30.046 --> 00:44:32.036 A:middle
subscription, we only renew it

00:44:32.036 --> 00:44:34.586 A:middle
after six times per eight-hour

00:44:34.586 --> 00:44:34.876 A:middle
window.

00:44:36.156 --> 00:44:37.626 A:middle
Then we let it expire.

00:44:37.816 --> 00:44:39.406 A:middle
So you can handle the case where

00:44:39.406 --> 00:44:40.436 A:middle
a user has actually let their

00:44:40.436 --> 00:44:41.496 A:middle
subscription lapse and you can

00:44:41.786 --> 00:44:43.056 A:middle
handle that in your application

00:44:43.056 --> 00:44:43.516 A:middle
accordingly.

00:44:45.536 --> 00:44:46.836 A:middle
When it comes to setting up this

00:44:46.836 --> 00:44:47.886 A:middle
test environment, it's done

00:44:47.886 --> 00:44:48.826 A:middle
through iTunes Connect.

00:44:49.406 --> 00:44:50.776 A:middle
You create test users in iTunes

00:44:50.776 --> 00:44:52.156 A:middle
Connect and you can just those

00:44:52.156 --> 00:44:53.146 A:middle
in-app purchase products that

00:44:53.146 --> 00:44:54.706 A:middle
you've already got for sale and

00:44:54.706 --> 00:44:55.946 A:middle
then you just build and sign

00:44:55.946 --> 00:44:56.886 A:middle
your app using XCode.

00:44:57.086 --> 00:44:58.206 A:middle
So it's built and signed using

00:44:58.206 --> 00:44:59.356 A:middle
the developer certificate.

00:44:59.816 --> 00:45:00.986 A:middle
And you just go ahead and buy

00:45:00.986 --> 00:45:02.016 A:middle
products in your application.

00:45:02.016 --> 00:45:03.346 A:middle
And when you're prompted to sign

00:45:03.346 --> 00:45:04.856 A:middle
in, you'll be able to sign in

00:45:04.856 --> 00:45:06.716 A:middle
using that test user that you

00:45:06.716 --> 00:45:07.656 A:middle
made in iTunes Connect.

00:45:08.906 --> 00:45:10.046 A:middle
One note if you are developing

00:45:10.046 --> 00:45:11.746 A:middle
for the Mac, you may need to

00:45:11.746 --> 00:45:13.146 A:middle
launch your app once from Finder

00:45:13.226 --> 00:45:14.716 A:middle
just in order to make sure that

00:45:14.716 --> 00:45:15.756 A:middle
the receipt gets fetched.

00:45:16.486 --> 00:45:18.146 A:middle
This is because that exit code

00:45:18.146 --> 00:45:19.006 A:middle
that we mentioned earlier on in

00:45:19.006 --> 00:45:21.106 A:middle
the talk where you exit 173 on a

00:45:21.106 --> 00:45:23.296 A:middle
Mac, well XCode catches that if

00:45:23.296 --> 00:45:24.066 A:middle
you're building and running

00:45:24.066 --> 00:45:25.156 A:middle
straight from XCode the first

00:45:25.156 --> 00:45:25.336 A:middle
time.

00:45:25.336 --> 00:45:26.126 A:middle
You need to make sure that you

00:45:26.126 --> 00:45:27.606 A:middle
launch the app once that binary

00:45:27.606 --> 00:45:29.036 A:middle
from Finder so that StoreKit can

00:45:29.036 --> 00:45:30.816 A:middle
catch that exit code and handle

00:45:30.816 --> 00:45:31.346 A:middle
it appropriately.

00:45:31.956 --> 00:45:34.476 A:middle
In terms of using the sandbox

00:45:34.476 --> 00:45:35.306 A:middle
from the server, I mentioned

00:45:35.306 --> 00:45:36.076 A:middle
that we have a different

00:45:36.266 --> 00:45:37.816 A:middle
endpoint for the verify receipt

00:45:37.816 --> 00:45:37.883 A:middle
url.

00:45:37.883 --> 00:45:39.826 A:middle
This is what it looks like in

00:45:39.826 --> 00:45:40.736 A:middle
the development environment.

00:45:40.736 --> 00:45:41.516 A:middle
You'll probably have your

00:45:41.686 --> 00:45:43.226 A:middle
developer signed app probably

00:45:43.226 --> 00:45:44.996 A:middle
talking to your test server and

00:45:44.996 --> 00:45:46.506 A:middle
that test server can talk to the

00:45:46.506 --> 00:45:47.716 A:middle
App Store sandbox by the

00:45:47.716 --> 00:45:48.406 A:middle
different url.

00:45:49.596 --> 00:45:50.346 A:middle
In production, you'll have

00:45:50.346 --> 00:45:50.946 A:middle
something like this.

00:45:50.946 --> 00:45:52.306 A:middle
Your production app will talk to

00:45:52.306 --> 00:45:53.936 A:middle
your production server and that

00:45:53.936 --> 00:45:54.996 A:middle
can talk to the production App

00:45:54.996 --> 00:45:56.626 A:middle
Store server but there is one

00:45:56.626 --> 00:45:57.906 A:middle
particularly case where there's

00:45:57.906 --> 00:45:58.756 A:middle
a bit of a mismatch.

00:45:59.806 --> 00:46:00.936 A:middle
And that's when your app is in

00:46:00.936 --> 00:46:01.516 A:middle
app review.

00:46:01.516 --> 00:46:04.026 A:middle
And why is it a mismatch?

00:46:04.026 --> 00:46:05.546 A:middle
It's because the app review team

00:46:05.546 --> 00:46:07.366 A:middle
actually uses a sandbox user to

00:46:07.366 --> 00:46:08.476 A:middle
be able to test your in-app

00:46:08.476 --> 00:46:09.146 A:middle
purchases.

00:46:09.876 --> 00:46:10.926 A:middle
So this is what that looks like.

00:46:10.926 --> 00:46:12.296 A:middle
You have your production signed

00:46:12.296 --> 00:46:13.986 A:middle
app talking to your production

00:46:13.986 --> 00:46:15.216 A:middle
server but you need to be able

00:46:15.216 --> 00:46:17.396 A:middle
to verify transactions for a

00:46:17.396 --> 00:46:18.736 A:middle
sandbox user just to get through

00:46:18.736 --> 00:46:19.826 A:middle
the app review scenario.

00:46:19.826 --> 00:46:21.136 A:middle
So how do you handle this

00:46:21.186 --> 00:46:22.056 A:middle
particular mismatch?

00:46:22.546 --> 00:46:23.616 A:middle
Well we have a way of doing

00:46:23.616 --> 00:46:23.866 A:middle
this.

00:46:24.836 --> 00:46:25.966 A:middle
Firstly, when you're in the

00:46:25.966 --> 00:46:28.756 A:middle
production environment try the

00:46:28.756 --> 00:46:30.306 A:middle
production App Store url first.

00:46:31.296 --> 00:46:32.526 A:middle
Now if the receipt is for the

00:46:32.526 --> 00:46:33.536 A:middle
sandbox, you'll receive a

00:46:33.536 --> 00:46:35.766 A:middle
specific error code, 21 double 0

00:46:35.766 --> 00:46:35.946 A:middle
7.

00:46:36.606 --> 00:46:37.526 A:middle
That's an indication that you

00:46:37.526 --> 00:46:39.556 A:middle
need to then to try against the

00:46:39.556 --> 00:46:40.966 A:middle
App Store sandbox instead.

00:46:41.406 --> 00:46:42.516 A:middle
So you can leave that in your

00:46:42.516 --> 00:46:43.716 A:middle
production environment and this

00:46:43.716 --> 00:46:44.586 A:middle
will just mean that your app is

00:46:44.586 --> 00:46:45.906 A:middle
able to sail through app review

00:46:46.146 --> 00:46:47.126 A:middle
without any problems in this

00:46:47.126 --> 00:46:47.436 A:middle
regard.

00:46:47.436 --> 00:46:50.516 A:middle
When it comes to the new server

00:46:50.516 --> 00:46:52.426 A:middle
to server notifications, this is

00:46:52.426 --> 00:46:53.456 A:middle
handled slightly differently.

00:46:53.456 --> 00:46:54.586 A:middle
So we don't actually have a

00:46:54.586 --> 00:46:56.206 A:middle
separate url in iTunes Connect

00:46:56.526 --> 00:46:58.166 A:middle
for a sandbox -- or for your own

00:46:58.166 --> 00:46:58.716 A:middle
test server.

00:46:59.686 --> 00:47:01.116 A:middle
We handle this sandboxing by

00:47:01.116 --> 00:47:02.416 A:middle
parameter in the actual payload

00:47:02.746 --> 00:47:03.666 A:middle
of the notification.

00:47:03.666 --> 00:47:04.846 A:middle
So there's an environment key

00:47:04.846 --> 00:47:06.226 A:middle
that you can use that'll tell

00:47:06.226 --> 00:47:06.856 A:middle
you whether or not the

00:47:06.856 --> 00:47:09.716 A:middle
